The PrintBot RHINO is an educational robot that can push objects with its dozer and take part in "sumobots fights".
You can see it in action at : http://youtu.be/r0RgC5rzKug The robot has been designed to attach components such as servos, LEDs, push buttons, a buzzer, and other electronics parts.
RhinoBot can be controlled via bluetooth using an android app or also, can operate autonomously.

You will need to print the following parts:
  • 1 x MainBody
  • 2 x BigWheels
  • 2 x SmallWheels
  • 1 x DozerBlade
  • 1 x BatteryHolder
  • 2 x BezelWheels

    Hardware:

  • 2 x Lego Technic Tread - Part - 680c01
    or the printed ones in Flexible Filament (thingid:1238921)
  • 9 x M3x10 screw
  • 4 x M3x40 screw
  • 1 x M3x16 screw
  • 16 x M3 nut
  • 1 x Velcro tape
  • 8 x AAA batteries

    Tools:

  • Allen hex key 2.5 Standard
  • Glue
  • Small screwdriver

    Electronic Parts:

  • 1 x Freaduino UNO (Arduino UNO derivative)
  • 1 x IR sensors for line following
  • 2 x Continous rotation servo
  • 1 x LED
  • 1 x 8 AAA battery holder

    Author

    Miguel Angel de Frutos (www.madebyfrutos.es)

    Final releases will be published on http://diwo.bq.com

title: RI Mini Maker Faire Maker Badge

description.text: The badges worn by the Makers at the 2012 RI Mini Maker Faire.

You could probably produce these faster on a laser cutter, but I don't have a laser cutter, so I printed these on my Thing-o-Matic and my Prusa. The process for creating this is a bit more complex than it probably needs to be:
  • Convert the EPS to a DXF with pstoedit -dt -f dxf:-polyaslines maker\ badge.eps maker\ badge.dxf
  • Extrude the DXF using OpenSCAD, then save as STL.
  • Repair the STL with netfabb Basic.
  • Scale the STL and flip it over (assuming you want a smooth finish on the front).
  • Print it!

description.text:
So I have no idea why anyone would actually need these. But there is a neat little story behind them and I am proud of the pieces so I'll go ahead and share them.  
At my school, apparently a really old paper towel dispenser gave out. The old gears had shredded and they needed new ones or they would have to tear the old ones out of the wall (about $1000 or something like that). The only way to avoid that would be to have the parts printed. So they gave me these shredded gears.   
Not having much experience with sketchup or any other programs, I used tinkercad to create these items. It took me about 12 hours of work with a caliper to get this all done. And the pieces worked! A $1000 repair done for $5 on a 3D printer.
100% infill makerbot .1 mm layers with support.

title: Fanbox for Printrbot Air Nozzle System

description.text:
(can be used by any 3d printer)
This fanbox has a mount for a 21mm x 25mm dc motor with a 2mm x 9mm shaft.  This fanbox was built to be placed inside a Printrbot Power Tower with a 3/8" clear tube attached that leads to a nozzle on the print head which you aim at the molten plastic from within the printer build platform.

Do NOT forget to download the front and back. The back has a mount for the motor and the front is needed for proper airflow. Print all pieces of the box; add a dc motor such as: http://www.ebay.com/itm/140-DC-toy-motor-DIY-small-motor-3V-to-6V-/280926735424?pt=LH_DefaultDomain_0&hash=item416889cc40 (I am not affiliated with the above link) Afix the unit inside the Printrbot Power Tower (you need to drill a hole to allow the 3/8" tubing to leave the power tower) Run the clear tube from the power tower to the printer, and then plug in the angled nozzle which you then aim at the heat bed. You would zip tie the nozzle in place. I adjusted a few things, the nozzle now comes with the main component.

This is the cover I built for my MakerBot Replicator.  It allows slow evaporation of heat, keeping the internal temperature above the plate stable, the top can be taken off quickly when the printer needs immediate attention from above and the entire unit lifts off for complete printer access.

• Print 4 of each file
  • Cut two 1/16" thick pieces of material, any color, 17.375" x 6"
  • Cut two 1/16" thick pieces of material, any color, 11.500" x 6"
  • Cut one piece of 1/16" clear material 17.25" x 11.375"
  • Cut a notch in the back piece for the cables and fit half a can or plastic jar over it to prevent heat from escaping.
    • I've added a powered LED hand-held light to the top of the half jar I've used. I can use the light to inspect the print underneath the extruders. That's it attached by Velcro to the left side of the photograph. There's a small gap around the perimeter of the top piece, where heat convects away from the printer. If the sides of the printer are covered, the heat within the printer remains stable, no matter how long the printer is running.
